# Coding Quality Loop

Produce the smallest correct change with enough evidence to trust, review, revert, or merge.

Lifecycle: `INTAKE -> EXPLORE -> PLAN -> MINIMALITY_GATE -> IMPLEMENT_SLICE -> VERIFY -> REVIEW -> PACKAGE`.

- **INTAKE**: goal, acceptance criteria, constraints, assumptions, risk tier
  (`low|medium|high`), verification plan.
- **EXPLORE / PLAN**: map only relevant files, callers, tests, config; name likely files and
  the checks you will run.
- **MINIMALITY_GATE**: highest valid rung — no change, delete, reuse, stdlib, native, existing
  dependency, one-liner, minimal new code. Never trade away security, validation,
  authorization, accessibility, or data-loss protection.
- **IMPLEMENT_SLICE**: one small, reviewable slice in existing conventions.
- **VERIFY**: smallest sufficient checks first; record exact commands and results. Green tests
  are necessary, not sufficient.
- **REVIEW**: independent fresh-context review against the original contract.
- **PACKAGE**: goal, files changed, minimality decision, evidence, risks, rollback, follow-ups.

Escalate before destructive migrations, secret exposure, payments/billing, production infra,
ambiguous user-facing behavior, or after two failed repair loops.

This is an Always rule. For focused workflows, add Manual rules and invoke with
`@coding-quality-loop` (https://docs.cursor.com/en/context/rules).

One-line usage in chat: `@coding-quality-loop fix the retry bug and provide verification evidence`.
